Repartition, versus coalesce, versus partition-by — three different things.

These three operations all have the word partition in the name, and they get confused constantly. But they do completely different jobs.

Repartition, of n, redistributes the rows across n partitions, in memory. It does a full shuffle. Use it to increase the partition count, or to rebalance.

Coalesce, of n, merges the existing partitions down to n, without redistributing. It does no shuffle — it is a narrow transformation. And it can only decrease the count.

Write dot partition-by, of a column, is completely different. At write time, it creates one on-disk subdirectory per distinct value of the column. We saw this back in module five. It has no in-memory effect — it only changes the file layout.

The key distinction is runtime versus write-time. Repartition and coalesce change how the rows sit in memory, for the next stage. Partition-by changes how they sit on disk, for downstream readers.

And there is one more form worth knowing — repartition of n and a column. This hash-partitions in memory, by that column, so all the rows with the same key value land in the same partition. Do this before a join on that column, and you eliminate the shuffle at join time.
